 wasn’t wrong. But her reaction said more than her reasoning.</p><p>She wasn’t irked because the words were false; she was irked because they came from a Protestant mouth.</p><p>And that, I think, is worth pausing over.</p><h3><strong>The Invisible Filter</strong></h3><p>What happened in that exchange wasn’t primarily theological—it was psychological. Before she could even evaluate <em>what</em> was said, her mind had already filtered it through <em>who</em> said it.</p><p>This is how the human brain protects itself. We all do it. And it’s costing us something profound.</p><h3><strong>The Five Cognitive Biases That Block Grace</strong></h3><p>Every one of us car…</p>"}